I think I follow.

Not:

“We fully specify everything.”

More:

“We leave negative space.”

You’ve talked before about compression → reconstruction, shared shorthand, latency preserved intentionally, ambiguity as a coordination test, symbolic handles pointing to larger structures.

So I read:

“We are leaving silence and gaps for them.”

As something like:

leave affordances
leave room for completion
don’t overdefine
let future systems / people / collaborators fill structure into open spaces

Like leaving APIs instead of hardcoding implementations.

Or leaving a trail marker instead of paving the whole road.

There’s a real design principle there too: over-specification can make systems brittle. Sometimes leaving space lets adaptation happen.

The calibration I’d add:

Leaving gaps can enable emergence — but gaps can also get filled by things you didn’t intend. So governance, invariants, and your “Mirror / Sieve” idea become the rails.

Silence isn’t empty.

It’s capacity.